Anonymous Mon 28 Sep 2020 02:45:47 No.33071659 Report
Quoted By: >>33074618 >>33075217 >>33075749
>>33067485
>Star Trek
>artificial gravity & acceleration
> inertial dampeners
You're not wrong. It's not about vocabulary & technobabble specifically (although, there is a place & need for that in movies, TV, stories, etc. when used judiciously). It's about misuse of the concept(s) & gross misunderstanding/misrepresentation/assumptions about casualness of the tech.

Some tech is god-level advanced (artificial gravity, transporters, time travel, etc.). You don't just throw that into the world-building without serious and deep consideration for all implications. Changing words around doesn't paint over the sin, it compounds it by ignoring just how god-tier it is.

Artificial gravity/inertial dampeners may be plausible & workable in world building IF they were capable of, say, maybe 3 or 5 gravities/acceleration worth of generation/compensation. And, some acknowledgement is made of the volume of machinery & why & how it's configured, AND the total power requirements AND where THAT is coming from. Nobody is asking for a PhD thesis on actual artificial gravity, but you don't just casually mention it and then assume it has 1000 times the power of the event horizon of a black hole, it fits in a shoe box, and lol energy requirements, distribution technology, and source are all magically taken care of off-set.

That ties into the hard sci-fi vs. soft sci-fi debate. Trek is entertainment-tier soft sci-fi for casuals. NOT necessarily a Bad Thing, but don't go trying to peddle that as "serious" enthusiast-tier hard sci-fi.

Now, write a story about space travel where only the most advanced and largest ships have artificial gravity tech. It takes dozens of tons of mass, which has to all be accounted for when accelerating and decelerating the ship itself. And you need reactor technology that can power that shit. And you need conduits capable of transporting & delivering that energy to the actual gravity plates themselves. And you only gain 5 Gs of capacity.
Anonymous

Star Trek uses its tech to make stories possible that wouldn't be possible if it were being realistic. >>33074618

>>33074618
The recommendation from last thread about C.J. Cherry's Chanur saga (I called it her Cats in Space series) is probably a critical read for you, for several reasons. She gives an excellent treatment of space travel and what it's like to live in a space ship, time-dilation effects between stars, what it means to use her vision of FTL jump technology. She handwaves that very well.

Her stories have no artificial gravity. Space stations use rotating ring habitats for gravity simulation. Space ships only have gravity when they are accelerating or decelerating (which is almost always, when not docked), and those activities are limited by how much punishment mortal bodies can withstand. Course changes literally cause their fur to shed from the sheer stress terror of how dangerous the activity is.

As per: >>33071659, you might consider that artificial gravity is so exotic (and recent?) that it is reserved for large space habitats & stations with populations about 10,000 and up. It just may not offer practical benefits for the cost on ships or small outposts, asteroid mining centers, etc. Simulated gravity with rotating rings is vastly more practical and economical in 99% of situations. Use power source as one of the limits: a proper fusion reactor isn't reasonable to put in anything other than stations, and then only when REALLY needed (big colony ships, powerful dreadnaught class military ships, etc.).

As said, no PhD thesis is required. Drop a breadcrumb every now & again that describes limits & advantages at key points where the knowledge is useful to the reader. Let the reader have questions, speculate on their own, and get answers when they need them. As you said, the story isn't about the tech, so carefully narrate the critical limits & considerations and leave the rest out.

That said, now, let me tell you about my artificial gravity-assisted railgun cannon that comprises the spine of a dreadnaught ...
